The Internet is a tool with great power to democratize, yet ironically, our own democracy can be pretty slow on the uptake. On Board is here to help.On Board is:
A database for local officials to more easily manage information about boards and commissions.
A website residents can use to find information about these bodies and get involved.
The result of 23 metro Detroit communities collaborating to engage more young people.
A prototype that some cities are already using to centralize information.
With support from the John S. and James L. Knight Foundation, Metro Matters is improving On Board and opening it up to more communities. We’re adding a ton of new features, like:
A notification system to help clerks manage board terms;
The ability to pull and download data reports;
A universal board application;
An API layer;
A widget for city websites so On Board can be fully integrated;
An OpenGov schema; and
A major redesign to improve the look, feel, and experience of the site.
But we still need help to make On Board awesome and spread the word to communities and residents. Become one of our first champions and help bring local government online!Why Communities Need On BoardNew technologies are critical to advancing good and open government, but many communities — especially small and medium sized local governments — have yet to embrace even the most basic tools. Let’s think about this for a minute. There are 35,879 cities, villages and townships in the United States and over 96 percent of these communities have less than 25,000 residents. 49 percent have less than 1,000.Local governments like these often rely on volunteers for assistance achieving public goals. In fact, there are over 5 million volunteers who serve on boards and commissions throughout the United States. These boards and commissions, such as the local planning commission or zoning board of appeals, have a lot of power when it comes to shaping our communities. If you try to look up these boards and commissions online however, chances are you’ll have a difficult time finding any information. This barrier to information often means that volunteers aren’t necessarily representative of the community. For example, young people (18-35) account for 29% of registered voters in metro Detroit, but only 6% of board and commission members.It’s not that local governments are intentionally exclusionary, but rather that getting all of this information on the web and managing the databases takes a lot of time and money. We at the Metro Matters, a 501(c)3 nonprofit in metro Detroit, hope to change this with On Board. For local officials, On Board is a secure database they can use to more easily manage information about boards and commissions. For residents like you and me, it’s a website we can use to find information about our local government and get involved.“The City of Ferndale is very excited to be selected to participate in the On Board pilot program. We have found the program very intuitive and easy to use. We hope the project will be expanded as this is a great tool to increase transparency and promote more participation in our city boards and commissions.”-Marne McGrath, Ferndale Deputy City ClerkUsabilityOn Board enables action through its ease of use. We knew we needed to make On Board useful and user-friendly to earn the buy-in of city clerks, mayors and managers, and to attract residents. Engagement of both residents and local officials are imperative to making On Board successful open gov tool, which is why we’ve engaged them early and often throughout its development.We Need Your Help!We have been fortunate enough to receive support from the Knight Foundation to build out the site’s features and functionality, but now it’s time to get communities and residents On Board! That’s where you come in.We’re hoping to get 1,000 donors because we know interest in using the tool is just as important as supporting it. Ideally, we’d like to achieve this goal in 60 days (16 people per day)  and raise $10,000.  These funds will be used to pay for a multi-pronged approach to raise awareness:
Printing and dissemination of marketing materials to municipalities, community groups and residents;
Radio placement via public radio;
Ads in municipal publications; and
Attendance at municipal and community conferences and conventions to present On Board to desired audiences.  
Any funds we raise will go toward this project, regardless of whether we reach or exceed our $10,000 goal. The more we raise, the more we can promote the site and help people engage with their communities. Who are we?Metro Matters is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit dedicated to advancing smart regional policy in metro Detroit. We work on issues like municipal finance reform, regional transit, infrastructure, social equity, and civic engagement.(Metro Matters the new name of the Michigan Suburbs Alliance. When you donate, you'll receive a thank-you note from the Michigan Suburbs Alliance nonprofit employer ID.)Our mission:We believe our interdependence is our greatest strength, and that opportunity grows when we act as one metropolitan Detroit. Through smart research, strategic advocacy, and creative storytelling, we engage Detroit’s diverse communities to advance metropolitan solutions to our shared challenges. Across the politics, issues and boundaries that shape our region, we proclaim: our Metro Matters.Learn more at OurMetroMatters.org.
“While technology has changed nearly every aspect of our lives, it is only beginning to affect the civic sphere. We see a tremendous opportunity in developing new technologies and approaches that can reinvent the way people relate to their governments, provide journalists the information they need and ultimately strengthen our democracy.” -Michael Maness, Knight Foundation Vice President for Journalism and Media Innovation
